p Life is a never-ending composite sine wave that rises (p) and falls (j) in an eternal cycle between awake (e) and asleep (i).

p An introvert is always ahead of the cycle, as their hypersensitivity to signals means they start earlier. They may not be able to identify the signal whose presence is preventing them from falling asleep in the evening because the signal is weak enough for other people to ignore, so they assume they should be able to ignore it also and don’t turn the signal down or off. They end up either not falling asleep at all (manic) or overdosing on the wrong sedatives and thus unable to wake up in the morning (depressed).

p An extrovert is always behind the cycle, as their obliviousness to signals means they start later. They may not be able to identify the signal whose absence is preventing them from waking up in the morning because the signal is strong enough for other people to perceive, so they assume they should be able to perceive it also and don’t turn the signal on or up. They end up either not waking up at all (depressed) or overdosing on the wrong stimulants and thus unable to fall asleep in the evening (manic).

p You can turn the signals on and off at will with the flick of a switch, or have them turned on and off for you by a timer set to your own preferred schedule. But which signals should you turn on and off when? That depends on your BipolarType.
